social_posts.post_text: A huge thank you to costume designer @_mitchelltravers_ for bringing me on to create the pirate masks for @shotgunweddingmovie It was such a treat working together to develop ideas, presenting quick sketches, and ultimately getting to fabricate these found object masks. This was a massive project that I could not have accomplished without the help of @edwinschiff With my crafty/paint hands and Edwin’s brilliant sewing skills we were able to fabricate about 15 unique designs; totaling more than 50 masks due to all the multiples required in the film. We spent a little over a month locked up in my parents house in Texas trying to get it all done. It was such a fun and chaotic time, especially considering it all happened during the Texas freeze of 2021. We had no power for a week and had to get creative jumping from friend house to friend house all to get the masks done on time. 😅🥶

When costume designer @_mitchelltravers_ said he wanted a skeleton face mask made out of soda tabs I got straight to work. The soda tab mask was one of the more complicated designs. It took about 3 days of hand sewing per each mask. There was a total of 10 masks because it was going to be lit on fire 🔥 @edwinschiff and I had to get extra hands in order to complete the project.  The balaclava is made of fire resistant fabric, the tabs were soaked in fire resistant  spray, and it was all sewn with fire resistant thread. We wanted to take every safety measure into account in order to insure the safety of the stunt man. ✨ @shotgunweddingmovie

The Bottle Cap Mask and the IKEA/Tarp Patchwork Mask are some of my favorites designs. The bottle caps were all sanded, painted, drilled, and linked together to create almost a chainmail feel. Thank you to @gabogenico & Javier for taking the time to drill all those countless holes for 3 masks worth of bottle caps and @edwinschiff for the full assembly. Working with costume designer @_mitchelltravers_ we focused on making the masks stylized enough to be memorable but just real enough that all the materials felt easily accessible to these pirates. @shotgunweddingmovie

More mask designs for @shotgunweddingmovie These designs  were more practical tactical masks with a decorative edge. The first mask had a full smile made of nails. I first filed down each nail for safety, stitched each one onto the mask, and then painted them to look rusted and tarnished. The other black mask was similarly distressed and costume designer @_mitchelltravers_ requested a skull. I used my hand print as the base of the skull design. The mask was actually a two face mask with the same skull design on both the front and the back. I added the construction site orange fencing as an over layer because it resembled the look of flames. It was a great way of adding a pop of color and making it feel more dangerous.🚧🔥

Here is the final round masks that were made for @shotgunweddingmovie Even though some of these didn’t make the cut, I’m so proud of the work that went into them.  The first mask is an actual soccer ball that I cut up and pitched as a mask. Second was made of chicken wire and a faux animal skull from online. Third is made to feel like the mouth of a sea creature. The cap with the horns is inspired by traditional Filipino warrior masks. The last mask is a traditional gas make made to feel industrial with sea elements. Thank you again to costume designer @_mitchelltravers_ for this giant creative opportunity. so grateful! And huge thank you to @edwinschiff for being my right hand on the project. ✨

Custom painted jacket for Showtime’s “George & Tammy” Costume Design by @_mitchelltravers_. The motifs on the jacket are based off an existing leather jacket George Jones wore during his career. Painting this jacket was challenging because the Navajo print needed to be so precise and clean. I painted this jacket using @angelusshoepolish paint and the smallest brush. 😅 Thank you, Mitchell, for always giving me a call when you have a fun project in mind. ✨ #georgeandtammy #michaelshannon #tammywynette

Custom mask for @servantofficial ✨ Thank you to costume designer @caroduncan for the creative call. Caroline wanted the mask to look like built up paint crackling to reveal the papier-mâché under layer. I used dictionary pages to layer and build it up from there. If you look close enough, I hid eerie dictionary text which is prevalent to the show for that extra dark factor.

Thank you @drosenorberg for bringing me on as the costume designer for this new adaptation of The Jungle Book. Huge thank you to Jennifer Love @jenniferlovecostumes for the incredible build of Baloo. In a little over a week Jennifer was able to create a bear suit so magical and lightweight for the actor to perform in. Thank you to Carmen Gee @carmengee24 for always having my back and building Mogli and the two little bears. Can’t describe how thankful I am for every friend who has had a hand in making these costumes happen. Textile More animal characters to come!✨

King Gibbon was actually inspired more by the rhesus monkey with a touch of Where the Wild Things Are. The suit came to life thanks to @seanbananofficial killer dance moves and personality. I imagined him a thief monkey who collects any shiny object trash or not. If you look closely his crown and cuffs are made to resemble canned food tins. Thank you to Carmen Gee @carmengee24 for the insane build of bodysuits, head pieces, tails, etc. There was a total of 20 suits built for the monkey gang. I had fun creating the jungle trash accessories. Thank you to @soy__louis for being the first fit model for the monkey suit! Also thank you to @ryanparkdesign and @sueann.leung for the final push with the last bit of head pieces.

Kaa the snake, played alluringly by @anna.norberg_ , was one of my favorite pieces I got to design. Her costume is inspired by the head of a cobra and the coiling movement of a snake. Jennifer Love @jenniferlovecostumes created this stunning piece of art. It was so beautifully striking and felt both dangerous and elegant. Huge shout out to Victoria Hohl, wardrobe supervisor, for dressing Anna and making this multilayer costume function successfully both on and off stage. ✨🐍#costumedesign

The Vultures were an unbelievably massive undertaking. Lucia Briones @lucybri83 took on the job of making these costumes fly😉. The bird shape was phenomenal and the wings moved beautifully. One of the key components for this design was to create the illusion of an elongated vulture neck.  Through a lot of R&D I think we really captured that magic. ✨ I can’t begin to thank Lucia enough. Not only did she make these costumes a reality, but she took the time to join me on my Swedish adventure. She has been my right hand on this trip and I am incredibly grateful to her for sharing her talents and friendship with me! She’s such a super star! 💕⭐️

I wanted the hyenas to feel scrappy and have a raised rib cage and outer skeletal design to signify their appetite for Mowgli. ✨#costume design

After four weeks of getting to shadow and assist, not only my friend but visionary costume designer, Wilberth Gonzalez, I’m excited to share a glimpse of this incredible rush and adventure. The days were long, the nights short and the wind was frigid but to get to witness these elevated and textural designs be brought to life by some of NYC’s finest costume makers, as well as the talented cast of #djungelboken, was an opportunity I will forever cherish. And even though he’s heard me say it a hundred times, I’m so proud of him 🥹 @viktoriaahohl, wishing you the best of luck this season! Couldn’t have completed all this without your finishing touch! 💜
